When I first started learning React Hooks, I thought they were simply a shorter way to write React components.
No classes. No constructors. No this.
Just functions.
But after working with React for a while, I realized Hooks solve a much bigger problem. They aren’t only about writing less code. They change how we organize and reuse logic inside components.
So instead of memorizing every Hook one by one, let’s understand why Hooks exist and where the commonly used ones actually fit.
Why Did React Need Hooks?
Before Hooks, stateful React components were mostly written using classes.
For a small component, that wasn’t a huge problem. But as applications grew, components often became difficult to manage.
A single component could contain API calls, subscriptions, form logic, event listeners, and state updates. Related logic was sometimes split across lifecycle methods such as componentDidMount and componentWillUnmount.
Reusing stateful logic was another challenge.
Developers relied on patterns such as Higher-Order Components and Render Props. They worked, but they could also add extra layers and make the component tree harder to follow.
Hooks approached the problem differently.
Instead of creating another component just to reuse logic, React allowed functions to access state, effects, context, and other React features.
That is the real idea behind Hooks.
Share stateful logic without sharing the state itself.
useState: Giving a Function Memory
Let’s start with the Hook almost every React developer learns first.
import { useState } from "react";function Counter() {
const [count, setCount] = useState(0); return (
<div>
<p>Count: {count}</p> <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
Increment
</button>
</div>
);
}A normal JavaScript variable doesn’t automatically cause React to update the screen when its value changes.
useState gives React a value to remember between renders.
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);Here, count contains the current state and setCount is used to request an update.
When the state changes, React renders the component again.
The important point isn’t the syntax.
Think of useState as component memory.
useEffect: Connecting React to the Outside World
useEffect is probably one of the most used and misunderstood Hooks.
You’ll often hear:
“useEffect runs after render."
That’s true, but it doesn’t really explain why it exists.
A better way to think about it is this:
useEffect helps a component synchronize with something outside React.
That might be an API, browser event, timer, WebSocket connection, or another external system.
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";function Users() {
const [users, setUsers] = useState([]); useEffect(() => {
fetch("/api/users")
.then((response) => response.json())
.then((data) => setUsers(data));
}, []); return (
<ul>
{users.map((user) => (
<li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
))}
</ul>
);
}Effects can also clean up after themselves.
useEffect(() => {
window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize); return () => {
window.removeEventListener("resize", handleResize);
};
}, []);This is especially useful for event listeners, subscriptions, and connections.
One mistake I see often is using useEffect for every piece of logic.
Not everything is an effect.
If a value can be calculated directly during rendering, you probably don’t need an Effect for it.
useContext: Escaping Prop Drilling
Imagine a theme value is needed deep inside your application.
Without Context, you might end up doing this:
App
↓
Layout
↓
Navbar
↓
Profile
↓
ThemeButtonEven components that don’t use theme may need to pass it down.
This is commonly called prop drilling.
useContext allows a component to read a Context value directly.
import { createContext, useContext } from "react";const ThemeContext = createContext("light");function ThemeButton() {
const theme = useContext(ThemeContext); return (
<button>
Current theme: {theme}
</button>
);
}Context is useful for values such as themes, authentication information, language preferences, and application-level configuration.
That doesn’t mean every state value belongs in Context.
Sometimes passing a prop is still the simplest solution.
useReducer: When State Logic Starts Getting Messy
useState works perfectly for simple state.
But consider a shopping cart.
You can add an item, remove an item, clear the cart, update quantity, or apply a discount.
At some point, multiple state updates become difficult to follow.
That’s where useReducer becomes useful.
import { useReducer } from "react";function cartReducer(state, action) {
switch (action.type) {
case "add":
return [...state, action.payload]; case "remove":
return state.filter(
(item) => item.id !== action.payload
); case "clear":
return []; default:
return state;
}
}function ShoppingCart() {
const [cart, dispatch] = useReducer(cartReducer, []); return (
<button
onClick={() =>
dispatch({
type: "add",
payload: { id: 1, name: "Keyboard" }
})
}
>
Add Item
</button>
);
}Instead of updating state from different places, we describe what happened.
dispatch({ type: "add", payload: item });The reducer decides how the state should change.
For complex state transitions, this can make the code much easier to reason about.
useRef: Remembering Something Without Re-rendering
Here’s an important question.
What if you want to store a value between renders but don’t want changing that value to re-render the component?
That’s where useRef comes in.
import { useRef } from "react";function InputFocus() {
const inputRef = useRef(null); const focusInput = () => {
inputRef.current.focus();
}; return (
<>
<input ref={inputRef} />
<button onClick={focusInput}>
Focus Input
</button>
</>
);
}Refs are commonly used for accessing DOM elements.
But they can also store mutable values.
const timerRef = useRef(null);Updating timerRef.current doesn't trigger a render.
That’s the major difference between useRef and useState.
useMemo and useCallback: Performance Hooks, Not Default Hooks
These two Hooks are often added to components far too early.
useMemo remembers a calculated value.
const filteredUsers = useMemo(() => {
return users.filter((user) => user.isActive);
}, [users]);useCallback remembers a function reference.
const handleSearch = useCallback((query) => {
searchUsers(query);
}, []);They can be useful when dealing with expensive calculations or preventing unnecessary work in memoized components.
But adding them everywhere doesn’t automatically make an application faster.
Memoization also has a cost.
My general rule is simple: find a performance problem first, then optimize it.
Don’t wrap every value in useMemo just because React provides the Hook.
useLayoutEffect: When Timing Really Matters
useLayoutEffect looks similar to useEffect, but its timing is different.
It runs after React updates the DOM but before the browser paints the screen.
This makes it useful when you need to measure or adjust layout before the user sees it.
useLayoutEffect(() => {
const width = boxRef.current.getBoundingClientRect().width; setWidth(width);
}, []);DOM measurements are a common example.
For most side effects, useEffect is the better choice.
Use useLayoutEffect when visual timing genuinely matters.
The Most Powerful Part of Hooks: Custom Hooks
Individual Hooks are useful.
But custom Hooks are where the design really starts to make sense.
Suppose multiple components need to track the browser width.
You could repeat the same state and event listener logic everywhere.
Or you could create this:
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";function useWindowWidth() {
const [width, setWidth] = useState(window.innerWidth); useEffect(() => {
const handleResize = () => {
setWidth(window.innerWidth);
}; window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize); return () => {
window.removeEventListener("resize", handleResize);
};
}, []); return width;
}Now any component can simply write:
const width = useWindowWidth();This is what made Hooks such an important change in React.
The components don’t share the same state.
They share the logic that manages that state.
That difference is easy to miss when you’re first learning Hooks.
Why Do Hooks Have Rules?
React Hooks come with two famous rules:

• Call Hooks only at the top level.

• Call Hooks only from React components or custom Hooks.
So why can’t we do this?
if (isLoggedIn) {
const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
}The reason is connected to how React tracks Hooks.
Conceptually, React relies on the order in which Hooks are called.
useState(...)
useEffect(...)
useRef(...)React expects that order to remain consistent between renders.
If a Hook suddenly appears or disappears because of a condition, the order can change.
React may no longer be able to associate the correct internal state with the correct Hook call.
The Rules of Hooks aren’t random restrictions. They make the Hook model possible.
Hooks Didn’t Just Replace Classes
It’s easy to describe Hooks as the feature that replaced class components.
I don’t think that’s the most useful way to understand them.
Hooks gave React developers a better way to organize stateful behavior.
State logic can live together.
Side effects can be extracted.
Reusable behavior can become a normal JavaScript function.
And we can do all of this without adding extra components to the render tree.
That’s why understanding Hooks is more important than simply memorizing their syntax.
You can learn useState in ten minutes.
The harder part is learning when state is actually needed, when an Effect is unnecessary, when a ref is a better choice, and when logic deserves its own custom Hook.
Once those decisions start making sense, React Hooks stop feeling like a collection of APIs.
They start feeling like a way of thinking about components.
